ce:section.ce:para:
Degradable implant materials offer significant advantages compared to permanent implants. The function of an implant is generally necessary until the injury has healed completely. For bone implants like plates, screws or nails for fixation of fractures, the use of degradable implants leads to no further surgery for removal. The implant material can be dissolved, absorbed, consumed or excreted in the physiological environment of the human body. Similarly, scaffolds for tissue engineering should be made of biodegradable materials [4]. Most of the biodegradable implants currently available are based on polymers. However, especially for applications like bone implants and scaffolds or stents, in which the mechanical properties are important, biodegradable polymers do not fulfil the necessary mechanical requirements [8,14,15]. Pure magnesium has high corrosion degradation rates and relatively low mechanical strength, which limits the application after implantation. Addition of alloying elements can improve the mechanical properties as well as the corrosion resistance; moreover, grain refinement can be beneficial for the alloy properties [16]. In turn, magnesium alloys have excellent mechanical properties: they are lighter in weight and more resistant to cracking than ceramic biomaterials, and both modulus and tensile strength are consistent with those of human bone [17]. Problems with the use of magnesium alloys as implant material are also high degradation rates, hydrogen evolution and alkalization due to the corrosion of magnesium in the body as well as containing high quantities of aluminum and rare earth elements, which are associated with toxic effects. Therefore, magnesium alloys with biocompatible alloying elements (Zn, Ca, Mn, Li, and Sr) are being increasingly investigated [18,19]. For example, lithium has no negative influence on cell viability or inflammatory response. Song et al. postulated that the amount of evolving hydrogen can be decreased and the corrosion stability can be enhanced by means of surface treatments [6,14]. Strategies to apply different coatings on Mg and Mg alloys have been reviewed [1,20,21]. In particular for orthopedic applications, coatings of hydroxyapatite have been used successfully. The use of calcium phosphate coatings on Mg to control the corrosion rates and to improve biocompatibility has been reviewed by Shadanbaz et al. [22]. In addition, Blind et al. [23] reported improved osseointegration due to hydroxyapatite coatings or proteins, which additionally can lead to better acceptance of the foreign body by the biological system. Synthetic hydroxyapatite has been demonstrated to have similar properties to natural calcium phosphates. Table 1
                      summarizes the calcium phosphate phases used for coatings in the orthopedic field. Moreover, bioactive glass containing coatings using biopolymers as matrix have been also reported [24–29] in order to provide corrosion protection and better bone bonding ability (Table 2
                     ). In addition, chemical conversion coatings are popular technologies to produce bioactive and corrosion resistant coatings. Until now, manganese, phosphate, and zinc composite conversion coatings were reported to be suitable for Mg and Mg alloys. For example, the microstructure and composition of Zn-Ca-P coatings on Mg-1.33Li-0.6Ca were characterized by Zou et al. [30]. The coating exhibited a flower-like crystalline morphology and showed significantly reduced corrosion compared to the pure alloy. Similar results were reported by Zeng et al. [31] on AZ31 alloy.
